            Hartley-Leonard, Darryl
        

           Aug 19, 2013
        

       Darryl Hartley-Leonard Nominated by American Hotel & Lodging Association (AHMA)  Inducted in 1991  Shaping the Industry A private investor, Darryl Hartley-Leonard served as the executive chairman and CEO of Production Group International, Inc. (PGI), one of the largest event companies in the world. PGI saw a future in one-stop management of events and meetings, and acquired production companies, destination services companies, and trade show organizers, bringing them all under one roof, to solidify that future.  Before joining PGI, Darryl spent a 32-year career with the Hyatt hotel company and its diversified affiliates. He first joined Hyatt in 1964 and served as its executive vice president since 1978. He also served as president of Regency Systems Solutions, a technology subsidiary of Hyatt. Later, Darryl served as chairman of the board of Hyatt Hotels Corporation from 1994 to 1996 and as its chief executive officer, president and chief operating officer from 1986 to 1994. Expansive Influence Darryl was a visionary, and in the early 1990’s, he made a prediction foreshadowing a dark period in hotel profitability. He warned his fellow hoteliers to "survive till '95" in a keynote speech at the American Hotel and Motel Association annual meeting, and at several other large meeting planner gatherings shortly thereafter. His prediction that the overbuilt hotel situation, coupled with an oncoming economic recession, would mean hard times for the hotel industry, but better rates for meeting planners, came true. Outstanding Service to Industry Organizations Darryl was a widely recognized as a credible voice for the industry for many years due to his service in other areas. He served as chairman of the U.S. Department of Commerce Travel and Tourism Advisory Board and as chairman of White House Conference on Travel and Tourism. Additionally, Darryl was the chairman of the Travel Business Roundtable and served as chairman of the Travel and Tourism Government Affairs Council.    





